<article>

  <p>
    Knowing that craving causes trouble is not yet
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammā-diṭṭhi" data-en="right view">sammā-diṭṭhi</span>
    — right view. That knowledge is common. It can live in the same mind that still
    reaches, consolidates a story, and calls the reaching inevitable. A diagnosis without
    origin, cessation, and path is still a view. It is not yet the factor the path depends on.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Sammādiṭṭhi
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span>
    (MN 9) is Sāriputta's answer to a sharper question: what does right view look like when
    it is working? The elder — regarded in the canon as foremost in
    <span class="pali" data-pali="paññā" data-en="wisdom">paññā</span>
    — does not offer a creed to memorize. He demonstrates a cut. Topic after topic, the same
    four questions return. By the end, the method has turned on the deepest conditions that
    keep confusion running. The Buddha confirms the discourse. The confirmation is not
    ceremonial. It names what has been shown: a way of seeing that arrives at true
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="teaching">Dhamma</span>.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Not the Correct Opinion</h2>

  <p>
    The ordinary misreading is managerial and doctrinal at once: collect the right
    Buddhist positions, discard the wrong ones, and call the collection right view. That
    reading flatters a mind that likes to be settled. It also turns the first path factor into
    an identity project — another set of claims to defend.
  </p>

  <p>
    English makes this easier than it should.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammā" data-en="right / complete">Sammā</span>
    is usually translated "right," and "right" leans toward correctness — the right answer,
    the right club, the right take. In the
    <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>,
    the sense is closer to complete, aligned, in accord with how things are. A view is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammā" data-en="right / complete">sammā</span>
    when it sees clearly — not when it matches a statement of faith. Creed-matching
    produces anxiety about belonging. Clear seeing produces a quieter pressure: is this
    lean, right now, feeding
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>,
    or interrupting it?
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course opinions matter. The tradition does not treat every metaphysics as equal,
    and living as if intentional action bears fruit — including beyond this life — still
    shapes what one is willing to say, take, or harm. That shaping improves this life either
    way. But MN 9 is not a catalogue of approved conclusions. It is a training in how to
    investigate what appears so that conclusions stop floating free of causes and endings.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Same Cut, Sixteen Times</h2>

  <p>
    Sāriputta's method is repetitive by design. He takes a series of topics and applies one
    four-part analysis to each: understand the thing, understand its origin, understand its
    cessation, understand the path leading to its cessation. The first application lands on
    the unwholesome and the wholesome —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="akusala" data-en="unwholesome">akusala</span>
    and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kusala" data-en="wholesome">kusala</span>
    — and already shows the pattern:
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "When a noble disciple understands the unwholesome, the root of the unwholesome,
    the wholesome, and the root of the wholesome — in that way, he is one of right view."
    <cite>— MN 9 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    That is not an accident of rhetoric. It is the structure of the four noble truths applied
    as a portable tool. Suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path are not only a
    doctrine about life as a whole. They are a template for looking at whatever is currently
    thickening experience — a craving, a nutriment, a link in the chain, a deep ferment.
  </p>

  <p>
    The pairing throughout is deliberate. Right view does not know only one side of a
    contrast. It knows the unwholesome and the wholesome; suffering and the ending of
    suffering; ignorance and what abandons it. A person who knows only that craving is
    harmful has a view. A person who knows what craving is, how it arises, what its
    cessation is, and what practice leads there has right view. The difference is not
    vocabulary. It is range.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What the Formula Does to an Ordinary Hour</h2>

  <p>
    Consider a familiar cascade. A pleasant contact arises — a message, a taste, a glance.
    Feeling-tone brightens. Reaching follows almost before the mind can name it. Then a
    thicker event forms: planning how to keep the pleasant, or how to avoid its loss. Most
    of an afternoon can be spent inside that manufacture without ever asking where the
    reaching came from or what its ending would mean.
  </p>

  <p>
    Apply Sāriputta's cut. What is present? Craving —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="tanhā" data-en="craving">tanhā</span>
    — as lean and pressure, not as a moral indictment. What is its origin? Contact meeting
    an untrained preference; contact conditioned by the six sense bases; the whole web the
    tradition maps as
    <a href="/concepts/paticca-samuppada/"><span class="pali" data-pali="paṭicca-samuppāda" data-en="dependent origination">paṭicca-samuppāda</span></a>.
    What is its cessation? The fading of that lean when conditions are no longer fed —
    not a dramatic annihilation fantasy, but the simple non-arising of the next surge. What
    is the path? The factors already named elsewhere: ethics that reduce remorse, attention
    that can notice the lean, unification that steadies the mind enough to see.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sutta begins earlier than craving, with the wholesome and unwholesome and their
    roots, then with nutriment
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="āhāra" data-en="nutriment">āhāra</span>)
    — what keeps a process going — and with
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
    itself. The point of those early movements is the same. Right view is not an abstract
    verdict on Buddhism. It is the habit of asking, of whatever is fueling the mind: what
    is this, what feeds it, what ends it, what practice ends the feeding?
  </p>

  <p>
    That habit is checked against what can be noticed, not against a finished cosmology.
    MN 9 does not ask for belief as a substitute for looking. It asks for investigation —
    the same spirit the
    <a href="/suttas/kalama/">Kālāma Sutta</a>
    protects when authorities disagree. Notes, not conclusions. And yet the notes have a
    direction: toward the ending of what is being fed.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Walking the Chain Backward</h2>

  <p>
    The long middle of MN 9 works backward through the twelve links: aging-and-death,
    birth, becoming, clinging, craving, feeling, contact, the six sense bases, name-and-form,
    consciousness, formations, ignorance. The
    <a href="/concepts/paticca-samuppada/">dependent origination</a>
    page maps that chain as a teaching in its own right. This discourse does something
    narrower and more demanding. It treats each link as a subject for the fourfold cut.
  </p>

  <p>
    The result is not a timeline of souls. It is a sequence of investigations. Aging-and-death
    can be understood; so can their origin in birth; so can their cessation; so can the path
    to that cessation. The same for clinging, contact, ignorance. Dependent origination
    stops being a diagram one recites and becomes a set of places where attention can look.
    Each link is something that appears in the texture of a life — not only as philosophy
    about rebirth, but as the thickening that follows contact here and now.
  </p>

  <p>
    Whether the full cosmological reading of the chain is ultimately true or not, living as
    if becoming is conditioned — as if clinging and craving are not free-floating choices
    but dependent events — still changes how tightly one grips. That change lands in this
    life either way. The sutta's confidence is practical: what is conditioned can, in
    principle, be known as conditioned. What can be known as conditioned can be released
    where the supporting conditions cease.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Where the Method Meets Its Own Root</h2>

  <p>
    MN 9 does not end at ignorance. It ends at the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="āsavā" data-en="taints; fermentations">āsavas</span>
    — the deep ferments the canon names as conditioning ignorance itself: sensual desire
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="kāmāsava" data-en="taint of sensual desire">kāmāsava</span>),
    desire for existence
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="bhavāsava" data-en="taint of becoming">bhavāsava</span>),
    and ignorance
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="avijjāsava" data-en="taint of ignorance">avijjāsava</span>).
    Their abandonment is how the texts mark full liberation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sāriputta applies the same formula one last time. Understand the taints. Understand
    their origin. Understand their cessation. Understand the path to their cessation. With
    that understanding — not as a proposition filed away, but as seeing that no longer
    feeds what seeps — the mind is described as liberated through non-clinging.
  </p>

  <p>
    The structural implication is quiet and severe. Right view begins the path as
    orientation. Practiced fully, it turns on the conditions that kept orientation cloudy.
    The factor that opens the training is also the factor that, matured, sees through what
    sustained confusion at the root. Nothing here pretends to settle what that final seeing
    is like from the outside. The discourse only shows the method that keeps refusing to
    stop one question early.
  </p>

  <p>
    A view that names the problem and stops is common. A view that keeps asking for
    origin, cessation, and path — until even the ferments come into range — is what MN 9
    calls right. The path spirals. It starts with seeing, and it ends with seeing that has
    nowhere left to hide.
  </p>

</article>
